**a.** The NPV or the net present value can be solved using the formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{NPV}&=-\text{Initial investment}+\text{Present cash flow value}
\end{aligned}$$

For the present cashflow value, we will simply take the OCF and multiply it to the annuity factor. The operating cash flow can be solved using this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Operating Cashflow}&=[(\text{Price}-\text{variable cost})\times \text{Quantity} - \text{Fixed Cost}]\\
& \times (1-\text{Time})+(\text{Time} \times \text{Depreciation})
\end{aligned}$$

**b.** Accounting break-even occurs at the point wherein the company has exactly zero net profit. This can be solved using:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Quantity}&=\dfrac{\text{Fixed Cost}+\text{Depreciation}}{\text{Price}-\text{variable cost}}
\end{aligned}$$

The cash break-even value refers to the point where in the cashflow is exactly zero. This can be solved using the formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Quantity}&=\dfrac{\text{Fixed Cost}}{\text{Price}-\text{variable cost}}
\end{aligned}$$

The financial break-even point refers to the number of units that make the NPV zero. In order for the NPV to be zero, the $OCF^*$ must be equal to the initial investment. The formula for the financial break-even point is:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Quantity}&=\dfrac{\text{Fixed Cost}+\text{Operating Cashflow}^*}{\text{Price}-\text{variable cost}}
\end{aligned}$$

**c.** The degree of operating leverage refers to how much the company's revenue is affected by a change in the quantity. 

This can be solved using:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Degree of Operating Leverage}&=1+\dfrac{\text{Fixed Cost}}{\text{Operating Cashflow}}
\end{aligned}$$
